social status, no château on Lake Geneva—Leith can scarcely imagine a salon, but she is drawn to Paris, and dreams of becoming a writer. This dream fuels her education in London, her marriage and writing in Budapest, and—finally—her journey back to Montreal where she meets a community of writers and readers who she works with to transform the city’s literary scene. As Leith publishes, translates, and curates, she also comes to terms with her troubled father and the secrets of her childhood. A luscious read, this book will rivet readers of Jill Ker Conway’s The Road from Coorain and Tara Westover’s Educated, or anyone who has dreamed of building a cultural life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAdolphe.  aAnglophone.  aBasel, Switzerland.  aBaslerdütsch.  aBaudelaire.  aBecoming a writer.  aBipolar disorder.  aBlue Metropolis Publishing.  aBudapest.  aCamden School for Girls.  aCanadian Literature.  aChange.  aCommunist Party.  aCommunity.  aDeath.  aDisowned.  aDivorce.  aDream City.  aDreams.  aFrench.  aGeneral Practitioner.  aGerman.  aGlamour.  aHaving it all.  aHaving it all?.  aHungarian.  aHungary.  aInspiration.  aIntellectual women.  aInternational.  aJohn Abbott College.  aLanguages.  aLatin.  aLisburn, Northern Ireland.  aLiterary career.  aLiterary women.  aLondon.  aMadame de Staël.  aMarriage.  aMavis Gallant.  aMcGill University.  aMemoir.  aMinority.  aMontreal.  aMotherhood.  aNapoleon.  aOutsiders.  aParis.  aPersonal independence.  aPh.D.  aPointe-Claire, QC.  aProustian madeleine.  aQuebec.  aRebellion.  aRefuge.  aRefugee.  aSalonnière.  aSamuel Beckett.  aSectarianism.  aTranslation.  aTwo Solitudes.  aUniversity of